---
import Base from "../../layouts/Base.astro";
import TracePlayer from "../../islands/TracePlayer.svelte";
import LessonNav from "../../components/LessonNav.astro";
import buggy from "../../../derived/multipacket/buggy.trace.json";
import procedural from "../../../derived/multipacket/procedural.trace.json";

// Buggy first: watch the message arrive scrambled, then watch sequence numbers put it back.
const registers = [buggy, procedural];
---

<Base
  title="Packet switching — GlassBox"
  description="Watch one message split into packets that take different routes, arrive out of order, and reassemble by sequence number."
>
  <LessonNav slug="multipacket" position="top" />

  <h1>Packets take different routes</h1>
  <p class="lede">
    A message does not cross the internet in one piece. It is chopped into numbered <em>packets</em>, each
    of which finds its own way to the destination — so they arrive <em>out of order</em> and have to be put
    back together by sequence number. Switch the abstraction on and watch three packets (the numbered dots)
    fan out across the network and reassemble at <code>D</code>.
  </p>

  <TracePlayer registers={registers} client:visible />

  <section class="explain card">
    <h2>What you are looking at</h2>
    <p>
      One message, three packets (<code>0</code>, <code>1</code>, <code>2</code>), each handed a different
      route from <code>A</code> to <code>D</code>. Packet <code>0</code> takes the long way, so it is sent
      first but arrives last — the packets reach <code>D</code> in the order <code>1, 2, 0</code>.
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <strong>Buggy</strong> — the receiver keeps the packets in <em>arrival</em> order, so the message
        reassembles as <code>[1, 2, 0]</code>: scrambled. Out-of-order delivery has corrupted it.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Procedural</strong> — the receiver sorts by sequence number (<code>sorted(arrived)</code>),
        restoring <code>[0, 1, 2]</code>. Split, route independently, reassemble in order — that is exactly
        what "packet switching" means, and why the network can route around trouble without losing the
        message.
      </li>
    </ul>
    <p class="fineprint">
      The packets' movements are real execution output; the little network is a hand-built model (marked <em>model: author-asserted</em>) — see <a href="../../verification/">how GlassBox stays honest</a>.
    </p>
  </section>
  <LessonNav slug="multipacket" position="bottom" />
</Base>

<style>
  .explain { margin-top: 1.4rem; }
  .explain ul { margin: 0.6rem 0; padding-left: 1.1rem; }
  .explain li { margin: 0.5rem 0; }
  .fineprint { color: var(--ink-faint); font-size: 0.9rem; margin-bottom: 0; }
</style>
